Back home, like two overlapping movies, the noise and mayhem at Kandanda House reached deafening levels, leading to an ongoing boycott of certain local sporting activities by a section of main stream media houses.
Mwendwa, who is in his second term as Football Kenya Federation president, has grown his list of enemies so much that it now includes chairmen of some top flight leagues, who should in fact be his key allies now that the management of the league is now a function of the federation. Needless to say, local mainstream media is firmly on the outside.





Besides that, there are many issues unsettled, including the salaries and allowances owed to national team players dating back to the Africa Women’s Cup of Nations in 2016.
Moreover, nothing has been heard of the recently elected women’s representative at the National Executive Council. Not even an outline of her plan or vision for women’s football, or if there are any structures to be put in place to grow women’s football in the country.
Granted, the women’s top flight league has kicked off, but the fear of frequent walkovers and mistreatment of players and technical bench members is yet to be addressed.
Trickier for the FKF leadership is how to assure the public that the grants from Fifa that are dedicated to women’s football are being put to good use, especially the Sh60 million meant for the Fifa Women’s Football Division pilot programme.



