After a coaching workshop and referees training seminar for former and current women footballers in 2018, as well as a leadership and governance worship for elected women representatives in January last year, nothing has been heard of the project.
The promise to establish U-13 and U-15 girls’ leagues in primary schools remains fresh in the minds of women’s football advocates, as well as the organisation of a girls’ youth festival as promised last year during a status visit by Fifa Chief of Women’s Football, Sarai Bareman in August last year.
The problem for the local FA president is that going into 2021, there is little to suggest that external parties are to blame for the bedlam at Kandanda House.
Now that his mandate is no longer under threat and sponsors are (seemingly) falling over themselves offering to sponsor local football, the ball is firmly in his court.
